<HEAD>Burglars Loot London Home of Sultan's Brother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burglars stole <MONEY>$6.5 million</MONEY> worth of jewelry and
cash from the <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> home of Prince <PERSON>Jefri Bolkiah</PERSON>, whose brother is
a sultan considered to be the world's richest man, police said
<DATE>Monday</DATE>.
   The intruders entered through a first-floor window of the red
brick house in the north <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> district of <ORGANIZATION>East Finchley</ORGANIZATION> late in
the afternoon <DATE>Thursday</DATE> or in the <TIME>evening</TIME>, said Detective
Superintendent <PERSON>David Staff</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Scotland</LOCATION> Yard.
   Police said details were being kept confidential at the sultan's
request.
   Prince <PERSON>Jefri</PERSON> is the youngest brother of the 42-year-old sultan of
<LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>, who has 37 words in his name and title but is generally
called Sir <PERSON>Hassanal Bolkiah</PERSON>. The sultan is worth an estimated <MONEY>$30
billion</MONEY> and is listed in the <ORGANIZATION>Guinness Book of World Records</ORGANIZATION> as the
world's richest man.
   Staff, the detective superintendent, said the prince's wife,
<PERSON>Princess Norhayti</PERSON>, was not at home when the robbery occurred.
   ``No physical violence'' was involved, he said, and the thieves
had ``no contact'' with any of the household staff or security
guards. He would not elaborate. He also would not say whether the
house had been ransacked or if selected items were taken.
   <PERSON>Fred McColl</PERSON>, the family's lawyer, said additional security
measures had been taken but he would not give details. Asked whether
former employees were being questioned, he replied: ``We are
questioning a number of people.''
   Newspaper reports said the gang must have had intimate knowledge
of the complex security systems and alarms in the house.
   <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>, on the northwest coast of <LOCATION>Borneo</LOCATION>, is rich in oil and
natural gas and the revenues go to the sultan, who also is prime
minister and defense minister. It is a former British protectorate
and became fully independent on <DATE>Dec. 31, 1983</DATE>.
   <LOCATION>Britain</LOCATION>'s record robbery was of an estimated <MONEY>$48 million</MONEY> from a
safe deposit center in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>Knightsbridge</LOCATION> district in <DATE>1987</DATE>. The
center's owner, <PERSON>Parvez Latiff</PERSON>, and three other men were convicted of
the crime last <DATE>January</DATE>.
</TEXT>
