<HL> Beverly Hills Hotel Is Sold
By Davis to Sajahtera Inc.</HL>
<DD> 10/07/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> REAL ESTATE, REITS, LAND DEVELOPMENT (REL) </IN>
<DATELINE> LOS ANGELES  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil man <PERSON>Marvin Davis</PERSON> said he sold the <ORGANIZATION>Beverly Hills Hotel to Sajahtera Inc</ORGANIZATION>. 
The price wasn't disclosed. 

   Spokesmen for <PERSON>Mr. Davis</PERSON> declined to provide any details about Sajahtera or to elaborate on a short press release. 
However, as previously reported, hotel sources have indicated the hotel was sold to the Sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION> for more than <MONEY>$200 million</MONEY>. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Davis</PERSON> purchased the hotel from the family of <PERSON>Ivan F. Boesky</PERSON> and others for about <MONEY>$135 million</MONEY> in <DATE>December</DATE>. 
The sale followed <PERSON>Mr. Boesky</PERSON>'s <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY> settlement of insider-trading charges brought by the <ORGANIZATION>Securities and Exchange Commission</ORGANIZATION>. 

   In its current issue, Fortune magazine pronounced the sultan the world's richest man, estimating his net worth at <MONEY>$25 billion</MONEY>. 
The sultan, who rules <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>, a tiny country on the oil-rich island of <LOCATION>Borneo</LOCATION>, lives in a 1,788-room palace and owns more than 200 polo ponies, according to the story. 

   The release said the new owners intend to pursue existing plans for "major improvements" to the posh pink hotel, which has 260 rooms and cottages. 

</TEXT>
