<HL> Trump Sniffs at Plaza Bid, Leaving a Sultan Sulking </HL>
<SO> </SO>
<CO> FREST </CO>
<IN> REL </IN>
<DATELINE> NEW YORK  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When <PERSON>Donald Trump</PERSON> bought the Plaza Hotel for roughly <MONEY>$400 million</MONEY> this year, the judgment of many real estate observers was that he paid too much. 

   Industry sources, however, say <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> already has received -- and rejected -- an offer for the Plaza that would have net him a <PERCENT>50%</PERCENT> profit. 

   The sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>, reputedly the world's richest person, recently offered to buy it for a little more than <MONEY>$500 million</MONEY>. 
When <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> declined, the sultan upped his bid to roughly <MONEY>$600 million</MONEY>, the sources say. 
But <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> said no deal. 

   The sultan apparently didn't get wind that the Plaza had been on the market before <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON>, who bought it from the <PERSON>Robert M. Bass Group</PERSON>, had more or less locked it up. 
"It was the one hotel he wanted to own more than any in the world," a source said of the sultan. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> declined to sell because he likes owning the famed, landmark hotel and wants to make good on his vow to make it the world's best, sources say. 
<PERSON>Mr. Trump</PERSON> declined to comment. 

   The ruler of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>, a tiny Asian nation on the oil-rich island of <LOCATION>Borneo</LOCATION>, has a fortune estimated at <MONEY>$25 billion</MONEY>, and lives in a 1,788-room palace. 

   Last year, the sultan bought the <LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION> Hotel from oil and entertainment tycoon <PERSON>Marvin Davis</PERSON>, reportedly for more than <MONEY>$200 million</MONEY> -- just months after <PERSON>Mr. Davis</PERSON> purchased it from one-time stock speculator <PERSON>Ivan Boesky</PERSON> for roughly <MONEY>$135 million</MONEY>. 

</TEXT>
