<HEAD>Baker, a Critic of Authoritarian Rulers, Rubs Elbows With Them on
Tour</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA_ ^Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MUSCAT, Oman (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> administration has welcomed the
global trend away from authoritarian rule, but at least two stops on
Secretary of State <PERSON>James A. Baker III</PERSON>'s swing through <LOCATION>Asia</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Europe</LOCATION> seem immune to such democratic changes.
   <PERSON>Baker</PERSON> has spent much of the past four days in <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Oman</LOCATION>,
both sultanates that are virtually devoid of the democratic
trappings normally advocated by the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>.
   In this <LOCATION>Arabian Peninsula</LOCATION> nation, there are no political parties,
no legislature and no elections. All power rests with <PERSON>Sultan Qaboos</PERSON>,
the latest in a line of monarchs who have ruled this Kansas-sized
land since the <DATE>1740s</DATE>.
   Baker decided to stop off in <LOCATION>Oman</LOCATION> mainly to rest before joining
President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> in <LOCATION>Poland</LOCATION>, the first stop on a four-nation European
tour.
   Oman was chosen in part because few Arab nations, if any, are
friendlier to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. Oman was one of the first Arab
nations that endorsed the <DATE>1978</DATE> Camp <PERSON>David</PERSON> peace agreement between
<LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Israel</LOCATION>.
   As authoritarian rulers go, <PERSON>Qaboos</PERSON> appears to be more benign than
most. When he deposed his father in <DATE>1970</DATE>, <LOCATION>Oman</LOCATION> was a land plagued by
poverty, disease and illiteracy.
   In <DATE>19 years</DATE>, <PERSON>Qaboos</PERSON> has been able to forge what is for the most
part a modern, prosperous nation, overcoming such obstacles as a
forbidding climate that often sends temperatures above 130 degrees.
   According to <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> figures, there were only three
schools in <LOCATION>Oman</LOCATION> in <DATE>1970</DATE>. In <DATE>1986</DATE>, there were 697. The number of
hospital beds rose from 12 to 2,800 in the same time period.
   Oil helped finance the boom, much as it did in <PERSON>Baker</PERSON>'s previous
stop, <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>.
   Unlike <LOCATION>Oman</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION> has a constitution, but it provides <PERSON>Sultan
Hassanal Bolkiah</PERSON> with supreme executive authority.
   The occasion for <PERSON>Baker</PERSON>'s visit to <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION> was the annual meeting
of the six-member <ORGANIZATION>Association of Southeast Asian Nations</ORGANIZATION>.
   Like <LOCATION>Oman</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION> has a system with a social conscience,
providing subsidized food, fuel, housing, free education and medical
care.
   <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>'s 250,000 citizens enjoy an unusually high standard of
living, which permits them to over look the opulent lifestyle of
their ruler and his two wives.
   The main attraction in <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>, about the size of <LOCATION>Delaware</LOCATION>, is the
sultan's palace, a 1,788-room extravaganza with a dining room
capable of accommodating 6,000 for a sit-down meal. Need a bathroom?
The palace has more than 200.
   Amid such abundance, the sultan is somewhat wary about
inquisitive reporters. Before the start of the <ORGANIZATION>ASEAN</ORGANIZATION> conference,
reporters were told to write about the conference, not about <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>.
   Still, the sultan has been unable to conceal his role as perhaps
the world's richest man, with an estimated wealth of <MONEY>$28 billion</MONEY>,
almost four times the gross national product of <LOCATION>Oman</LOCATION>.
   He is one of a handful of men who has claim to a fortune that
dwarfs the estimated <MONEY>$3 billion</MONEY> to <MONEY>$5 billion</MONEY> of <LOCATION>Zaire</LOCATION>'s autocratic
president, <PERSON>Mobutu Sese Seko</PERSON>, the last foreign leader whom <PERSON>Baker</PERSON>
entertained before departing on his tour.
</TEXT>
