<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A <ORGANIZATION>GROUP of Labour</ORGANIZATION> MPs <TIME>last night</TIME> accused the <ORGANIZATION>High Commission of Brunei</ORGANIZATION> in
<LOCATION>London</LOCATION> of failing to honour debts incurred by sponsored students from the
<LOCATION>Sultanate</LOCATION>.
In a motion tabled under parliamentary privilege, the MPs called on the
Sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION> to 'meet the debts owed by his <ORGANIZATION>High Commission</ORGANIZATION> to landlords
and other debts in the <LOCATION>United Kingdom</LOCATION>'.
The MPs, led by <PERSON>Mr Nigel Griffiths</PERSON> (<ORGANIZATION>Edinburgh South</ORGANIZATION>), said the commission
had failed to honour payments owed to the landlords of properties rented by
their students.
They added that promissory notes issued by the High Commissioner in the name
of the Sultan were 'worthless'. The <ORGANIZATION>High Commission</ORGANIZATION> failed to honour the
securities it had given to creditors.
The motion said that the High Commissioner had failed to answer
correspondance from solicitors and MPs and warned all universities of the
'financial unreliability' of the <ORGANIZATION>High Commission</ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
