<LP>
   BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- The Beverly Hills Hotel is
planning a major renovation that's likely to result in the
temporary closing of the famous complex, which is known as
the "Pink Palace" from its outside color scheme.
   But Kerman Beriker, general manager and chief executive
officer, disputed a report in yesterday's Los Angeles
Business Journal that quoted industry insiders as saying the
hotel planned to close for two years, starting next
September. The article said the renovation would cost $150
million, not including lost revenue. "It's very premature,"
Mr. Beriker said. "Nobody really knows when we can start."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Mr. Beriker</PERSON>, however, said that the almost 80-year-old
hotel is in dire need of a makeover. "To be a five-star
hotel, you need to have a five-star facility . . . and we
don't have it." He said that the hotel filed papers with the
<ORGANIZATION>City of Beverly Hills</ORGANIZATION> three weeks ago seeking various
building permits.
   The hotel is owned by the Sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>, one of the
world's wealthiest individuals, who purchased it from oil and
film tycoon <PERSON>Marvin Davis</PERSON>. In <DATE>1986</DATE>, <PERSON>Mr. Davis</PERSON> bought the
hotel, a longtime oasis for the rich and famous, from <PERSON>Ivan F.
Boesky</PERSON>, the arbitrager who pleaded guilty to insider-trading
charges.
</TEXT>
