<HEAD>Sultan's Heir Officially Attains Adulthood</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of <LOCATION>Southeast Asia</LOCATION> and
local royalty welcomed the 15-year-old future ruler of this tiny
oil-rich nation into the adult world <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> by sprinkling
scented water on his hands.
   Cannons fired in salute and thousands of Bruneians watched on TV
to watch the ritual for Prince <PERSON>Al-Muhtadee Billah</PERSON>, the son of
Sultan Hassanal Bolkia.
   Leaders from <LOCATION>Indonesia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Singapore</LOCATION> and
<LOCATION>Thailand</LOCATION>, as well as 3,000 other VIPs, including members of the
royal family, government dignitaries and foreign diplomats, were
invited to the two-hour ceremony in the throne hall of the sultan's
1,778-room palace.
   The pomp and pageantry, a combination of Islamic ritual and
Malay culture, were actually a commemoration of Prince <PERSON>Billah</PERSON>'s
circumcision, a momentous event in the life of Malay Moslems.
   Even though the prince, eldest son of the 43-year-old sultan,
was circumcised a few years ago, the ceremonies were dubbed
``berkhatan'' _ Malay for circumcision.
   ``Coming of age is a more appropriate term,'' an official said,
but tradition dictates that such ceremonies be called berkhatan.
   A weeklong festival for the occasion began <DATE>Sunday</DATE> with the
beating of gongs and playing of pipes and other ethnic musical
instruments at the main gate to the 300-acre palace grounds.
   The streets of the capital were decorated with multicolored
lights and yellow Bruneian flags fluttering from the top of
virtually every building.
   Until <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>, however, the ceremonies had consisted of solemn
prayers, chants of religious hymns and nightly poetry readings at
the palace.
   A few hours before <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>'s rites, the sultan, cited by the
<ORGANIZATION>Guinness Book of World Records</ORGANIZATION> as the world's wealthiest man, threw
an elaborate dinner at the cavernous royal banquet hall, whose
arches are covered with 22-carat gold tiles.
   His guest list was headed by President <PERSON>Suharto</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Indonesia</LOCATION>,
President <PERSON>Corazon Aquino</PERSON> of the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> and Prime Ministers <PERSON>Lee
Kuan Yew</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Singapore</LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Chatichai Choonhavan</ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION>Thailand</LOCATION> and
<PERSON>Mahathir Mohamad</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION>.
   In declaring the sultan the world's richest individual, <ORGANIZATION>Guinness</ORGANIZATION>
said that as its absolute ruler, he has <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>'s oil income and
foreign exchange reserves of about <MONEY>$30 billion</MONEY> ``effectively at his
disposal.''
   After all guests were seated, about 100 men and boys marched up
the middle of the hall, bearing Prince <PERSON>Billah</PERSON>'s regalia. They
included spears, swords, shields, rifles, pennants, candles, drums,
brass vases and urns.
   Behind them walked the young prince, in a green costume gleaming
with gold embroidery. Light from 12 giant chandeliers _ each with
600 bulbs _ reflected off the gems on his headdress.
   The normally shy boy appeared nervous. Just before Moslem
priests began chanting praise to <LOCATION>Allah</LOCATION>, Prince <PERSON>Billah</PERSON> rose from his
cushioned throne-like chair, set under a gold-colored canopy.
Apparently realizing the miscue, he quickly sat back, his head
bowed slightly.
   As the chanting began, the boy's parents, the leaders and other
guests came forward one by one and sprinkled scented water on his
hands, resting on a cushion on his lap. Outside, cannons boomed.
   Prince <PERSON>Billah</PERSON> is the third of the sultan's six children by <PERSON>Queen
Saleha</PERSON>, his first wife, but the elder of two boys. The sultan has a
son and two daughters by his second wife, <PERSON>Queen Mariam</PERSON>.
   On <DATE>Thursday</DATE>, the prince will undergo a cleansing ceremony in the
privacy of his apartments. Officials say the equivalent of this
rite for commoners is a swim in a river.
   After that, 25,000 children and other residents are expected to
line the streets of <PERSON>Bandar Seri Begawan</PERSON> to cheer Prince <PERSON>Billah</PERSON> as
he rides past on a float.
   Ceremonies at the palace are to continue through <DATE>Sunday</DATE>.
</TEXT>
