<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Elliott Abrams, the State Department's top
officer for Central America in the mid-1980s, admitted in
federal court to withholding information from Congress
regarding secret White House efforts at the time to arm
anti-Sandinista guerrillas in Nicaragua.
   Mr. Abrams, a former assistant secretary of state, pleaded
guilty to two misdemeanor charges as part of an agreement
under which he must cooperate in a continuing investigation
of the Iran-Contra affair by Independent Counsel Lawrence
Walsh.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   <PERSON>Craig Gillen</PERSON>, <PERSON>Mr. Walsh</PERSON>'s associate counsel who
represented the prosecutor at the court proceedings, was
cautious in assessing <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON>'s value to the inquiry. But
as a senior <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> administration official, <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON> moved
in high circles and could shed light on the activities of
<ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Central Intelligence Agency</ORGANIZATION> officers in
connection with the same covert supply network.
   <PERSON>Duane Clarridge</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Central Intelligence Agency</ORGANIZATION> officer who
had been closely involved in the anti-Sandinista war, has
been identified as a target of <PERSON>Mr. Walsh</PERSON>'s inquiry. And the
prosecutor has given immunity to a former associate of <PERSON>Donald
Gregg</PERSON>, a national security adviser to then-Vice President
<PERSON>Bush</PERSON> and now <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION>South Korea</LOCATION>.
   The charges against <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON>, which carry a maximum
penalty of one year in prison for each count, are themselves
the product of an earlier agreement in which <PERSON>Mr. Walsh</PERSON>'s
office won the cooperation of <PERSON>Alan Fiers</PERSON>, who headed the
<ORGANIZATION>CIA</ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION>Central America</LOCATION> task force in the mid-80s. <PERSON>Mr. Fiers</PERSON>
also pleaded guilty to withholding information from <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>,
and his testimony was instrumental in the case against <PERSON>Mr.
Abrams</PERSON> and in the more serious perjury charges brought last
month against the <ORGANIZATION>CIA</ORGANIZATION>'s former operations chief, <PERSON>Clair
George</PERSON>.
   With his hands clasped behind his back, the 43-year-old
<PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON> answered simply "I plead guilty" after <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION>
district <PERSON>Judge Aubrey Robinson</PERSON> read each of the counts
against him. In a brief statement later, <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON> showed
flashes of his old defiance, but he was a far more subdued
figure than the brash assistant secretary who symbolized a
generation of young neo-conservatives in the <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON>
administration. Many, like <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON>, had watched <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>
from academic campuses and had little patience with <ORGANIZATION>Congress</ORGANIZATION>
as they waged their proxy wars against communism from the
halls of <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>.
   A former <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> aide, <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON> infuriated Republicans
and Democrats alike in the <LOCATION>Capitol</LOCATION>, and yesterday's charges
focus on misleading testimony he gave in <DATE>October 1986</DATE> after a
cargo plane ferrying supplies to the Contras was shot down in
<LOCATION>Nicaragua</LOCATION>. Appearing before <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>House</ORGANIZATION> committees, <PERSON>Mr.
Abrams</PERSON> sought to distance the <PERSON>Reagan</PERSON> administration from the
supply network, and though he had directly solicited a <MONEY>$10
million</MONEY> contribution from the sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION> two months
earlier, he denied that foreign governments were helping the
Contras.
   At the time of his testimony, the administration was only
days away from overturning a ban on <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> funding for the war.
In a statement of facts accompanying yesterday's plea
agreement, <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON> is said to have feared that this
appropriations legislation would be lost if members learned
of the network.
   As assistant secretary, his specific knowledge grew out of
a close working relationship with <PERSON>Mr. Fiers</PERSON> and Marine Lt.
Col. <PERSON>Oliver North</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> aide who oversaw the supply
operation and served on a restricted interagency group headed
by <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON>.
   Beginning in <DATE>1985</DATE>, the court papers said, <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON>
became "generally aware" that Col. North was working with the
Contras, and he and <PERSON>Mr. Fiers</PERSON> had specifically discussed
using the <ORGANIZATION>White House</ORGANIZATION> aide's "private benefactor" network in
<DATE>July 1986</DATE> to get food to the insurgents when a government
"humanitarian" aid program ran out of funds.
   Using the pseudonym "Kennilworth," <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON> met with a
representative of the sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION> in a <LOCATION>London</LOCATION> park in
<DATE>August</DATE> that <DATE>summer</DATE>. The court papers show that before his
testimony in <DATE>October</DATE>, he was privy to subsequent <ORGANIZATION>State
Department</ORGANIZATION> cables showing that the sultan had agreed to give
<MONEY>$10 million</MONEY> and sent the money on to a Swiss bank account
that Col. North told <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON> about.
   Standing before television cameras later, <PERSON>Mr. Abrams</PERSON>
restated his guilty plea, but said the information withheld
had only to do with activities "which at that time I believed
to be proper and lawful." The former assistant secretary, the
first <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> official to be charged by <PERSON>Mr. Walsh</PERSON>,
expressed pride in his government service, but said he was
"very happy to have this entire matter at long last behind
me."
</TEXT>
