<HL> 

War in Los Angeles:
Luxury Hotels Battle
To Lure Glitzy Guests
---
Inns Old and New Also Fight
Over Art, French Toast;
How Boesky Was Outbid
---
Try the $3,000-a-Night Suite
---
By Kathleen A. Hughes
Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal</HL>
<DD> 12/07/87</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<IN> REAL ESTATE, REITS, LAND DEVELOPMENT (REL) </IN>
<DATELINE> LOS ANGELES  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Who cares where <PERSON>Julio Iglesias</PERSON> sleeps? 
To hoteliers <PERSON>Jacques Camus</PERSON> and <PERSON>Charles Ferraro</PERSON>, it is a weighty matter. 

   Their obsession with the nocturnal habits of the Spanish crooner is just one manifestation of the luxury-hotel wars here, wars in which sleeping celebrities are among the key signs of victory. 

   Many of the nation's cities have competitive hotel markets, but nowhere is the competition so consumed with glamour, glitz and gossip as in status-conscious <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>. 
Top hotels have changed hands here like hot potatoes in recent years, and a score of new ones have popped up, inspiring some cut-throat tactics. 

   "There's a special aura to these hotels," says <PERSON>Arthur Hailey</PERSON>, who wrote the novel "Hotel." 
"It's the aura of the entertainment industry and the old <ORGANIZATION>Hollywood</ORGANIZATION>. 
The magic still lingers." 

   Perhaps in search of such magic, <PERSON>Mr. Iglesias</PERSON> has proved peripatetic. 

   "<PERSON>Julio Iglesias</PERSON> always stays here," says <PERSON>Mr. Camus</PERSON>, the general manager of the tony <ORGANIZATION>Westwood Marquis Hotel</ORGANIZATION> and Gardens as he gestures toward a display of celebrity photographs in his office. 
"He left two weeks ago." 

   He did indeed. 
At the new Four Seasons Hotel a few hours later and a few miles away, <PERSON>Mr. Ferraro</PERSON>, the general manager, points toward a guest room. 
"<PERSON>Julio Iglesias</PERSON> is in there," he says, a smile creasing his face. 

   <PERSON>Mr. Iglesias</PERSON> presumably had enough choices. 
The number of first-class hotels has surged to 134 from 86 just <DATE>eight years ago</DATE>, and the flurry of feisty new contenders is forcing some of the more staid old hostelries to undertake multimillion-dollar renovations. 
Partly because of the newcomers, overall occupancy rates slid to <PERCENT>73%</PERCENT> from <PERCENT>79%</PERCENT> even before the stock-market plunge, helping to keep hoteliers on their toes. 

   Not only are they on their toes; they are also slugging it out. 
Battles are fought over such weighty matters as who sleeps where, which power-breakfast chef makes the best French toast and who has the most expensive art. 

   Some of the campaigns in these wars aren't directed by general managers but by high-powered marketing and public-relations people. 
And camouflage is an important weapon: coats of fresh paint that mask worn-out wood balustrades, and legendary hotel names that mask Motel 6-sized rooms. 
The Four Seasons hired not one but two public-relations firms, and many a hotel is spending <MONEY>$40 million</MONEY> and up on that Hollywood tradition: the facelift. 

   The <DATE>October</DATE> stock-market collapse made some luxury-hotel guests stay home, and some hotels said business was off <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>15%</PERCENT> as a result. 
Guests at the opulent <ORGANIZATION>Hotel Bel-Air</ORGANIZATION> made "quite a few changes of plans rather suddenly," says resident manager <PERSON>George Goeggel</PERSON>. 
Some guests, he says, "had to jet out fast." 
But business at most of the hotels has returned to normal. 
"Them that have always will have," says <PERSON>Mr. Ferraro</PERSON> at the Four Seasons. 

   Recruits to the hotel wars in the past few years include some of the world's wealthiest individuals. 
Dallas heiress <PERSON>Caroline Hunt</PERSON> added the <LOCATION>Bel-Air</LOCATION> to her group of hotels after an intense bidding battle. 
In <DATE>September</DATE>, the man reputed to be the world's richest, the sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>, apparently bought the <LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION> Hotel from oil and entertainment tycoon <PERSON>Marvin Davis</PERSON> -- just months after <PERSON>Mr. Davis</PERSON> purchased it from onetime stock speculator <PERSON>Ivan Boesky</PERSON>. 

   And just last month, entertainer <PERSON>Merv Griffin</PERSON>, best known for his 23-year stint as a talk-show host, agreed to buy the <ORGANIZATION>Beverly Hilton Hotel</ORGANIZATION>. 
A Japanese concern also bid for the hotel, and Japanese are expected to show continued long-term interest in the market. 
"They already own most of the major hotels in downtown <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>, and they'll continue to pursue the purchase of the premier hotels in the city," says <PERSON>John Cushman III</PERSON>, the president and chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION>Cushman Realty</ORGANIZATION>. 

   The hotels weren't always so hot hereabouts. 

   "Prior to 10 years ago, <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION> wasn't known as a good hotel market," says <PERSON>Saul F. Leonard</PERSON>, a partner at <ORGANIZATION>Laventhol &amp; Horwath</ORGANIZATION>, the accounting and consulting firm. 
But with the city's growth as the <LOCATION>West Coast</LOCATION>'s financial hub and the gateway to the <LOCATION>Pacific Rim</LOCATION>, businessmen with expense accounts have clamored for first-class hotel rooms. 

   Guests, who typically shell out <MONEY>$175</MONEY> to <MONEY>$300</MONEY> a night for a single (the price can go up to <MONEY>$3,000</MONEY> for the ne plus ultra in sybaritic surroundings), are being pampered with larger rooms or suites, real marble bathrooms with television, phones with more than one line, plush robes, exotic flowers and complimentary wine. 
A decade ago they would have been lucky to get a book of matches. 

   "We're all trying to outdo one another," says <PERSON>Michael Ullman</PERSON>, the general manager of the <ORGANIZATION>Beverly Hills Hotel</ORGANIZATION>. 
Some are even opening nightclubs. 
Last <DATE>August</DATE> the <ORGANIZATION>Mondrian Hotel</ORGANIZATION> on the Sunset Strip opened <PERSON>Piet</PERSON>'s Place, a hot outdoor Friday-night spot that has attracted people like actor <PERSON>Timothy Hutton</PERSON>, musician <PERSON>Elvis Costello</PERSON> and tennis star <PERSON>Chris Evert</PERSON>. 
The club is moving to warmer quarters at the Bel Age Hotel for the winter. 

   Much of the activity has been spurred by the Four Seasons, which opened only <DATE>last April</DATE> after a painfully long gestation period. 
The hotel, a pleasant but not architecturally spectacular 16-story residential tower, has been an aggressive self-promoter. 
A cocktail party in a tent six months before the hotel even opened drew the likes of <LOCATION>Zsa Zsa Gabor</LOCATION> and <PERSON>Henry Mancini</PERSON>. 
The group feasted on fried rabbit and oysters with leeks, bacon and periwinkles. 

   Hoteliers, however, scoff at the suggestion that the new hotel is hurting them. 
"Some of our bathrooms are larger than their rooms," says <PERSON>Severyn Ashkenazy</PERSON>, the owner of eight luxury hotels, including <LOCATION>L'Ermitage</LOCATION>. 
"Someone who would stay at the Four Seasons isn't our type of guest. 
He is the guest of hotel chains." 
But at least one hotelier, the late <PERSON>Hernando Courtright</PERSON>, fought hard to keep the new contender out. 

   Toronto-based <ORGANIZATION>Four Seasons Hotels Ltd.</ORGANIZATION> began searching for a location here six years ago and finally found the ultimate spot: posh <ORGANIZATION>Rodeo Drive</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION>. 
That is when <PERSON>Mr. Courtright</PERSON> was galvanized into action. 
The longtime owner of the <ORGANIZATION>Beverly Wilshire Hotel</ORGANIZATION>, diagonally across from the site desired by the Four Seasons, lobbied heavily against a city zoning change that would have permitted the project. 
<LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION> residents finally decided the issue at the polls, and the Four Seasons was sent packing. 
It wound up in a building just outside the <LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION> city limits. 

   The <ORGANIZATION>Beverly Wilshire</ORGANIZATION> itself was snapped up last year by <ORGANIZATION>Regent International Hotels</ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION>Hong Kong</LOCATION>, for <MONEY>$125 million</MONEY>. 
The new owners are sinking <MONEY>$50 million</MONEY> into renovations so that all the rooms will soon feature such necessities as marble bathrooms -- just like the Four Seasons. 

   The high cost of keeping up with competition was a big factor in <PERSON>Marvin Davis</PERSON>'s decision to part with the pink-stuccoed <ORGANIZATION>Beverly Hills Hotel</ORGANIZATION> despite a strong personal attachment to the show-business hangout. 
After buying it from <PERSON>Mr. Boesky</PERSON> in <DATE>December 1986</DATE> for <MONEY>$136 million</MONEY> (after <PERSON>Mr. Boesky</PERSON> had agreed to pay the government <MONEY>$100 million</MONEY> to settle insider-trading charges), <PERSON>Mr. Davis</PERSON> explained that he wanted the hotel partly because he spent his honeymoon there and he used to live and conduct business in one of its bungalows. 

   In recent months, the portly billionaire usually could be found presiding over meals in the hotel's famous Polo Lounge from the vantage point of table No. 3, a high-profile spot near the door. 

   But after learning that renovating the sometimes musty 75-year-old hotel would cost more than twice the <MONEY>$40 million</MONEY> originally estimated, <PERSON>Mr. Davis</PERSON> readily accepted a bid of around <MONEY>$200 million</MONEY> from an offshore company said to be an alter ego of the sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>. 
The sultan, ruler of a small oil country on <LOCATION>Borneo</LOCATION>, already owns the <ORGANIZATION>Dorchester Hotel</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>. 

   Another oil-rich innkeeper is <PERSON>Ms. Hunt</PERSON>, daughter of the late oil man <ORGANIZATION>H.L. Hunt</ORGANIZATION>. 
Her Hotel Bel-Air is the only hostelry here with a five-star rating from the <ORGANIZATION>Mobil Travel Guide</ORGANIZATION>. 
The mission-style hotel is set on 11 acres in a secluded canyon and features a pond filled with swans. 
Monaco's late Princess Grace and actress <PERSON>Kathleen Turner</PERSON> have been guests. 
<PERSON>Patti Davis</PERSON>, the president's daughter, was married there. 

   <PERSON>Ms. Hunt</PERSON>, who says owning a hotel means "you never have to feel lonely," had to compete against <PERSON>Mr. Boesky</PERSON> five years ago to buy the <LOCATION>Bel-Air</LOCATION>. 
It was a close call. 
<PERSON>Ms. Hunt</PERSON> won it with a bid a mere <MONEY>$8,370</MONEY> higher than <PERSON>Mr. Boesky</PERSON>'s. 

   She won, oddly enough, thanks to the suite number of her <ORGANIZATION>Rosewood Hotels Inc</ORGANIZATION>. 
Both sides had decided independently to bid <MONEY>$22.7 million</MONEY> plus a bit more. 
But <PERSON>Mr. Boesky</PERSON> set his bid at <MONEY>$22,729,000</MONEY> by using the numbers in his lawyer's birthday (<DATE>July 29</DATE>, or 7/29). 
<PERSON>Ms. Hunt</PERSON>'s team settled on a bid of <MONEY>$22,737,370</MONEY> because at the time <ORGANIZATION>Rosewood Hotels</ORGANIZATION> occupied suite <DATE>3737</DATE> in a downtown <LOCATION>Dallas</LOCATION> office tower. 

   The hotel competition has inflicted some battle wounds. 
<PERSON>Mr. Ashkenazy</PERSON>, a Polish-born real-estate developer, opened five west-side luxury hotels in eight years amid criticism that the projects were creating a glut. 
"The west side is the creative heart and soul of <LOCATION>Los Angeles</LOCATION>," <PERSON>Mr. Ashkenazy</PERSON> explains. 
But 20 months ago the hotelier's company filed for bankruptcy protection, blaming rapid expansion and a poor turnout for the <DATE>1984 summer</DATE> Olympics. 

   "He wanted to be <ORGANIZATION>Hilton</ORGANIZATION>, but even <PERSON>Mr. Hilton</PERSON> didn't open 10 hotels overnight," says <PERSON>Mr. Camus</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Westwood Marquis</ORGANIZATION>. 

   But the bankruptcy filing hasn't stopped <PERSON>Mr. Ashkenazy</PERSON>. 
He has since opened three additional hotels in <LOCATION>Hollywood</LOCATION> and plans to open his ninth area hotel next month. 
The <PERSON>Ashkenazy</PERSON> hotels are mavericks in the local market. 
The Mondrian, for example, is painted in a geometric pattern using 54 colors to resemble a Mondrian painting. 
The hotels are packed with original art from <PERSON>Mr. Ashkenazy</PERSON>'s personal collection, part of which he got in exchange for free rooms at his hotels. 

   Despite all the glitz, most of the luxury hotels compete mundanely, using direct mail, print advertising and appeals to travel agents. 
And most aren't above discounting. 
Although room rates range from <MONEY>$175</MONEY> to <MONEY>$3,000</MONEY> (for the Plaza Suite at the <ORGANIZATION>Century Plaza Hotel</ORGANIZATION>), many of the hotels give corporate discounts of <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> or more. 
Many of the luxury hotels have raised prices by about <PERCENT>10%</PERCENT> in the past two years. 

   A battle on a smaller scale is taking place in bathrooms, which at newer hotels are increasingly bristling with free deodorant and perfumes. 
And that is causing some older hotels to review their bathroom supplies. 
The <LOCATION>Beverly Hills</LOCATION>, for example, is considering adding guest slippers. 

   Some guests clearly care more about a hotel's style than about bathroom amenities. 
<PERSON>Michael O'Donoghue</PERSON>, a former producer of "<DATE>Saturday</DATE> Night Live" and a founder of <ORGANIZATION>National Lampoon</ORGANIZATION>, recently stayed at the Chateau Marmont while working on a script. 
The hotel, built in the style of a French chateau, isn't big on amenities. 
The coffee, <PERSON>Mr. O'Donoghue</PERSON> says, is terrible. 

   "Ambiance is why I stay here. 
It has a sense of history," he explains. 
He says that the hotel staff doesn't turn down the sheets or leave little mints on the pillows at night, but that's all right. 
To trick a friend staying at the hotel into thinking that <PERSON>Mr. O'Donoghue</PERSON> was being treated better than his friend was, <PERSON>Mr. O'Donoghue</PERSON> once brought in his own box of mints and turned down the sheets himself. 

</TEXT>
