<HEAD>Leaders Still Hope For Peaceful Settlement in Cambodia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Moerdiono is cq in 15th graf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIGUEL C. SUAREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANDAR SERI BEGAWAN, Brunei (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Non-Communist <LOCATION>Southeast Asia</LOCATION>
leaders are disappointed by talks in <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> to end 10 years of war
in <LOCATION>Cambodia</LOCATION> but still hope for a peaceful settlement, <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION>'s
prime minister said <DATE>Thursday</DATE>.
   The foreign ministers of 19 countries, who met this week in
<LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>, set up working committees to help monitor <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION>'s
withdrawal from <LOCATION>Cambodia</LOCATION> and an ensuing cease-fire, deal with
sovereignty questions and plan for repatriation of refugees.
   But talks between Cambodian Premier <PERSON>Hun Sen</PERSON> and leaders of the
three-party Cambodian resistance alliance led by Prince <PERSON>Norodom
Sihanouk</PERSON> reached an impasse <DATE>July 25 after two days</DATE> of negotiations.
   The talks were aimed at bringing warring Cambodian factions
together and ensuring peace after <LOCATION>Vietnam</LOCATION> withdraws its troops from
<LOCATION>Cambodia</LOCATION>, which it has occupied since <DATE>December 1978</DATE>.
   ``We are a little bit disappointed,'' said Malaysian Prime
Minister <PERSON>Mahathir Mohammed</PERSON>. ``But we are realistic people. We know
we can't resolve things by sitting and looking at each other. More
discussions are needed.''
   Mahathir made the statement between meetings with Indonesian
President <PERSON>Suharto</PERSON>, President <PERSON>Corazon Aquino</PERSON> of the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> and
Prime Minister <PERSON>Lee Kwan Yew</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Singapore</LOCATION>.
   Mahathir is scheduled to meet Prime Minister <PERSON>Chatichai
Choonhavan</PERSON> of <LOCATION>Thailand</LOCATION> when the Thai premier visits <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION> on
<DATE>Friday</DATE>.
   Southeast Asian leaders were gathered here for <DATE>Wednesday</DATE>'s rites
symbolizing the ``coming of age'' of the eldest son of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>'s
<PERSON>Sultan Hassanal Bolkiah</PERSON>.
   <LOCATION>Indonesia</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Malaysia</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Singapore</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Thailand</LOCATION> are
<LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>'s partners in the <ORGANIZATION>Association of Southeast Asian Nations</ORGANIZATION> _
the main proponents of the <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> conference.
   ASEAN, <LOCATION>China</LOCATION>, the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and other Western countries back
<PERSON>Sihanouk</PERSON>'s alliance, which includes the <ORGANIZATION>Khmer Rouge</ORGANIZATION>, whom the
Vietnamese drove from power.
   Vietnam does not want the <ORGANIZATION>Khmer Rouge</ORGANIZATION>, blamed for slaughtering
hundreds of thousands of Cambodians during their three years in
power, to play a major role in any new government.
   In <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Hun Sen</PERSON> blamed the faction for the breakdown in talks
among the various Cambodian factions. He said the <ORGANIZATION>Khmer Rouge</ORGANIZATION>
refuses to resume the talks.
   ``This is a problem that cannot be resolved overnight or over
one month,'' <PERSON>Mahathir</PERSON> said. ``We've been working on it for years.''
   A spokesman for <PERSON>Suharto</PERSON> told reporters earlier that the
Indonesian president and <PERSON>Mahathir</PERSON> agreed during their meeting that
prospects for peace in <LOCATION>Cambodia</LOCATION> remain good.
   But the spokesman, <PERSON>Moerdiono</PERSON>, would not elaborate. He said
<PERSON>Mahathir</PERSON> and <PERSON>Suharto</PERSON> agreed to meet again in <LOCATION>Bali</LOCATION> later this year
to review the Cambodian situation and discuss other issues.
</TEXT>
