<HEADLINE>
FT  27 OCT 94 / Government Ethics Row: The implausible guardian of morals
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN PLENDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<PERSON>Mr Mohamed Fayed</PERSON>, the Egyptian-born businessman who runs the Harrods
department store in <LOCATION>Knightsbridge</LOCATION>, is an implausible guardian of British
public morals. Yet it cannot be denied that he has shown a remarkable and
consistent knack of exposing double standards in the <LOCATION>City</LOCATION>, government and
the press.
Before the mid-1980s, when he and his brothers came to public attention
because of their bid for the <ORGANIZATION>House of Fraser</ORGANIZATION> stores group, <PERSON>Mr Fayed</PERSON> had sat
on the board of <PERSON>Mr Tiny Rowland</PERSON>'s controversial international conglomerate,
<ORGANIZATION>Lonrho</ORGANIZATION>, and acted as a middleman for British contractors in the <LOCATION>Gulf</LOCATION>. How he
progressed from there to acquiring sufficient funds to launch a cash bid
that valued <ORGANIZATION>House of Fraser</ORGANIZATION> at Pounds 615m has never been satisfactorily
explained.
Leading merchant bankers in the <LOCATION>City</LOCATION> were nonetheless prepared to take this
potentially lucrative client at his own valuation. Chief among them were
<PERSON>Kleinwort Benson</PERSON>, one of whose then directors, <PERSON>Mr John MacArthur</PERSON>, declared
on television at the time that he personally knew the net worth of the
Fayeds to be <MONEY>several billion dollars</MONEY>. In the light of subsequent events the
inquiries that supported this assertion appear to have been less than
rigorous.
Nor did the <ORGANIZATION>Department of Trade</ORGANIZATION> or the <ORGANIZATION>Office of Fair Trading</ORGANIZATION> look far into
the Fayeds' background. The secretary of state, <PERSON>Mr Norman</PERSON> (now Lord) <PERSON>Tebbit</PERSON>,
waved through the bid within 10 days, relying heavily on the names of the
professional advisers, who included <ORGANIZATION>City</ORGANIZATION> lawyers <PERSON>Herbert Smith</PERSON> alongside
<PERSON>Kleinworts</PERSON>.
The press was equally uncritical, giving credence to stories circulated by
City public relations man <PERSON>Mr Brian Basham</PERSON>. The Fayeds' fortune, according to
<PERSON>Mr Basham</PERSON>, derived from a cotton empire founded by their great grandfather
in the <DATE>19th century</DATE>, which then expanded into shipping as they exported
their wares to the mills of <LOCATION>Lancashire</LOCATION>.
The first indication that these stories were questionable emerged when <PERSON>Mr
Rowland</PERSON>, who believed that the Fayeds had deceived him over their intention
to buy <LOCATION>Harrods</LOCATION>, started a public campaign to discredit the brothers, dubbing
them 'the phoney pharoahs'. Subsequent independent inquiries by the
<ORGANIZATION>Financial Times</ORGANIZATION> and a Channel Four television documentary did indeed
discover that the Fayed brothers' origins and funds were not what they
claimed.
The findings were later confirmed by a <ORGANIZATION>Department of Trade</ORGANIZATION> inspectors
report. The inspectors concluded that the Fayeds 'dishonestly misrepresented
their origins, their wealth, their business interests and their resources to
the secretary of state, the <ORGANIZATION>Office of Fair Trading</ORGANIZATION>, the press, the <ORGANIZATION>House of
Fraser</ORGANIZATION> board and <ORGANIZATION>House of Fraser</ORGANIZATION> shareholders, and their own advisers'.
Among other things, it emerged that <PERSON>Mr Mohamed Fayed</PERSON>'s colourful past
included an adventure in the <DATE>1960s</DATE> in which he absconded with Dollars
100,000 belonging to the Haitian government of '<ORGANIZATION>Papa Doc</ORGANIZATION>' <PERSON>Duvalier</PERSON>. He was
known in this impoverished <LOCATION>Caribbean</LOCATION> country as a Kuwaiti sheikh.
The Arab equivalent of the particule nobiliaire - Mohamed 'Al' Fayed - was
adopted in the early <DATE>1970s</DATE>. By the <DATE>1980s</DATE> <PERSON>Mr Fayed</PERSON> had become an adviser to
the Sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>. Through a power of attorney he also had access to the
Sultan's bank account. While the <ORGANIZATION>DTI</ORGANIZATION> inspectors were unable to prove that
the Sultan's money paid for the bid, they concluded that this was the most
likely explanation for the Fayed brothers' sudden ability to finance a huge
takeover bid.
The connection with the <PERSON>Sultan</PERSON> also opened important doors, notably that of
No 10 Downing Street before the bid. <PERSON>Mr Fayed</PERSON> has claimed in the press that
he was instrumental in persuading the Sultan not to withdraw <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>'s funds
from sterling. He also claims to have persuaded the Sultan not to take
defence contracts elsewhere.
Despite the fact that the Fayed brothers clearly deceived the government, no
action was taken by ministers to disqualify them as directors of a public
company. This inertia has never been satisfactorily explained, although the
late <PERSON>Nicholas Ridley</PERSON>, when trade and industry secretary, justified the
decision not to pursue the brothers by saying that no shareholder had
suffered and that the matter was trivial.
What was not made public at the time was that <PERSON>Mr Fayed</PERSON> had privately donated
Pounds 250,000 to Tory party funds. Whether the new independent commission
of inquiry under <PERSON>Lord Nolan</PERSON> will take such a relaxed view remains to be
seen. The grant of money to Tory party funds was confirmed to the <ORGANIZATION>Financial
Times</ORGANIZATION> by a spokesman for <PERSON>Mr Fayed</PERSON> last week. It appears to cast the
government's weak response to the <ORGANIZATION>DTI</ORGANIZATION> inspectors' findings in a new and
dramatic light.
Nor have the inspectors' findings loosened all ties with the <ORGANIZATION>Fayeds</ORGANIZATION>'
professional and establishment friends. <PERSON>Herbert Smith</PERSON> continued to act for
<PERSON>Mr Mohamed Fayed</PERSON>'s business interests after the publication of the
inspectors' report - this despite the report's revelation that a <PERSON>Herbert
Smith</PERSON> partner had been systematically deceived on a trip to <LOCATION>Egypt</LOCATION> to inquire
into the Fayeds' origins and wealth.
While <PERSON>Kleinwort Benson</PERSON> parted company with <ORGANIZATION>House of Fraser</ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON>Mr MacArthur</PERSON>
continued to act as a consultant to the Fayeds. Nor was former minister <PERSON>Mr
Neil Hamilton</PERSON> alone in having enjoyed hospitality at the <ORGANIZATION>Fayeds</ORGANIZATION>' <LOCATION>Paris Ritz</LOCATION>.
Several establishment and showbusiness personalities went there when <PERSON>Mr
Fayed</PERSON> completed the restoration of the late Duke of <LOCATION>Windsor</LOCATION>'s <LOCATION>Paris</LOCATION> home.
So, too, did leading journalists. There is a striking correlation between a
number of the beneficiaries of this largesse and uncritical press comment,
including the designation of <PERSON>Mr Fayed</PERSON> as <ORGANIZATION>Mohamed 'Al</ORGANIZATION>' Fayed.
The Queen, meanwhile, continues to meet <PERSON>Mr Fayed</PERSON> at the <ORGANIZATION>Windsor Horse Show</ORGANIZATION>,
which derives support from <LOCATION>Harrods</LOCATION>.
Although the Fayed brothers have spent large sums in an attempt to
rehabilitate their reputation, they have never sued those in the media who
revealed their deceptions before publication of the <ORGANIZATION>DTI</ORGANIZATION> inspectors' report,
which enjoys qualified privilege in terms of libel.
Nor did their case against the <ORGANIZATION>DTI</ORGANIZATION> inspectors in the <ORGANIZATION>European Court of Human
Rights</ORGANIZATION> meet with success - in spite of the court's known reservations about
the department's investigation process.
<PERSON>Mr Fayed</PERSON> has frequently claimed that he wants British justice. Given that he
has never refuted the claims produced by his critics, the question <PERSON>Lord
Nolan</PERSON> might be tempted to ask is why British justice has not been visited
upon him.
</TEXT>
