<HEAD>London's Dorchester Hotel To Close For Facelift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The <LOCATION>Dorchester</LOCATION>, one of <LOCATION>London</LOCATION>'s most exclusive
hotels, will close in <DATE>December</DATE> for more than a year for a <MONEY>$134
million</MONEY> facelift.
   It will be the first closure in the hotel's 57-year history.
   The hotel, situated in <LOCATION>Park Lane</LOCATION>, was bought for <MONEY>$80 million</MONEY>
three years ago by the world's richest man, the Sultan of <LOCATION>Brunei</LOCATION>,
who pledged to make it the most luxurious in the world.
   A hotel spokesman said on <DATE>Tuesday</DATE> that major improvements
include an Oriental restaurant, a nightclub, a health club and news
conference rooms. The kitchens, plumbing and electrical system also
are to be upgraded.
   The hotel will close on <DATE>Dec. 23</DATE> and reopen sometime in the
<DATE>spring of 1990</DATE>.
